photo.description: H.E. Luxmoore Everdon Rectory 10 April 1866 Ownership inscription of Henry Elford Luxmoore (1841-1926) Lower inscription: A. Lamont Probably Austin Lamont (1905-1969), son of Thomas W. Lamont, banker at JP Morgan after whom Harvard's Lamont Library is named. According to this article in Anesthesiology, Austin Lamont was "originally planning to study classic Latin and Greek at the New College, Oxford University, England, [but] he changed his mind while still on the steamship headed for Europe." He instead studied science and became a doctor and professor of anesthesiology at the University of Pennsylvania School of Medicine (1947-mid1960s). Austin and his 2nd wife Bodine were Philadelphia elites and associated with other prominent Philadelphians Carl and Laura Zigrosser. Carl Zigrosser was a prints curator at the Philadelphia Museum of Art and member of the Print Club (Philadelphia). A finding aid to Zigrosser's papers is available here. Other examples of Austin Lamont's autograph. Penn Libraries call number: LatC C4855.10 1546 All images from this book

photo.description:
Ornamental woodcut border with images of biblical scenes (Adam and Eve's creation, Temptation and Fall from Paradise), angels, David and Moses.


Contains the author's L' Acerba, an allegorical poem of encyclopedic range, consisting of four books. The first book treats of astronomy and meteorology; the second deals with stellar influences, physiognomy, vices and virtues; the third with minerals and the love of animals; and the fourth propounds and solves a number of moral and physical problems.

Text is illustrated with 77 woodcuts, depicting astronomical knowledge, women (illustrating vices and virtues), and dozens of woodcuts of animals.

The author was eventually burned at stake in 1327 for his defense of astrology and other subjects that were considered dangerous by the Inquisition.


Penn Libraries call number: IC C3230 476a 1514

photo.description:
Possibly from an antiphonary; contains music and text for antiphon ("Num qui redditur pro bono malum, quia foderunt foveam animae meae"), notation for chanting its associated psalm, and music and text for hymn ("Lustra sex qui iam peregit" -- a portion of the "Pange Lingua" of Fortunatus, here as revised by Pope Urban VIII) associated with lauds of Passion Sunday. Probably not earlier than 1632, when Urban's revisions to the breviary were first published.

photo.description:

Also contains notation for chanting their associated psalms. Probably not earlier than 1632; cf. its fellow for justification.

photo.description: beati Rhenani sum. Nec muto d{o} minum An. m d xvij. [Dated ms. ownership inscription of the Alsatian humanist Beatus Rhenanus (1485-1547). In 1517 he was resident in Basel, Switzerland (and had just broken off his previous working relationship with the printer Johann Froben; cf. his exchange with Erasmus in letters nos. 594 and 628 in The Correspondence of Erasmus: Letters 594-841, ed. R.A.B Mynors and D.F.S Thomson (Toronto: Toronto UP, 1979).) After his death Rhenanus's library passed almost completely intact to the Humanist Library of Sélestat, his hometown. Cf. "Beatus Rhenanus's Books", an English translation of an article which first appeared in Histoire des bibliothèques françaises, tome 1: Les bibliothèques médiévales du VIe siècle à 1530 (Paris: Promodis, 1989), p. 298-301. photo.description: Bookplate: Sir George Shuckburgh Bart. Armorial bookplate (with ms. shelf-mark "T4") of Sir George Augustus William Shuckburgh-Evelyn, 6th Baronet (1751-1804), English politician (MP for Warwickshire 1780-1804), mathematician and astronomer. The lunar crater Shuckburgh is named after him. A Fellow of the Royal Society, he was the 1798 co-winner (with chemist Charles Hatchett, discoverer of niobium) of the Copley Medal. photo.description: Bookplate of Samuel Weiller Fernberger (1887-1956) Samuel Weiller Fernberger (1887-1956) received his Ph.D. in psychology from the University of Pennsylvania in 1912 and was a member of the faculty at Clark University from 1912 until his death. F. W. Irwin wrote in Fernberger's obituary in The American Journal of Psychology, Vol. 69.4 (1956), p. 677-678: "At all stages of his career he exhibited an interest in those applications of experimental psychology that employed rigorous, preferably psychophysical, methods. He once testified before the Public Service Commission of Pennsylvania as an expert for the complainant in an action brought by the Yellow Cab Company of Philadelphia to prevent the use by others of taxicabs with colors alleged to resemble too closely the color of Yellow Cabs. His testimony involved not only verbal opinions but also the performance of demonstrations in the hearing room in the presence of the examiner and the interested parties. He mixed colors on a rotary color mixer to match the colors of the complainant's and respondent's cabs, showed that they were closely similar -- they differed by not more than three just noticeable differences along the base of a model of the color solid that was also produced -- and that their resemblance increased as the illumination of the room was decreased." Shortly before his death Fernberger donated a collection of psychological books and journals to the University of Pennsylvania as the Samuel W. Fernberger Collection of Psychology.
